│ **Understanding the Issue**: The transformation in `foldLogicOfFCmps`         │
│ incorrectly assumes that the negation of `RHSC` will match `LHSC` when their  │
│ bitwise representations are equal. However, the debugger reveals that         │
│ `LHSC->bitwiseIsEqual(neg(*RHSC))` evaluates to `false`, indicating a         │
│ mismatch in the negation logic.\n\n2. **Analyzing `opt`'s Log**: The          │
│ transformation replaces the `select` instruction with a `fabs` operation and  │
│ a single `fcmp`. This replacement introduces poison when the negation logic   │
│ fails, as seen in the Alive2 counterexample.\n\n3. **Root Cause Analysis**:   │
│ The issue lies in the assumption that `LHSC` and `RHSC` are exact negations   │
│ of each other. This assumption fails due to the way `APFloat` handles         │
│ negation and bitwise equality.\n\n4. **Proposed Edit Points(s)**:\n   - File: │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp`\n   - Lines:        │
│ 1511-1541\n   - Fix: Add a check to ensure that                               │
│ `LHSC->bitwiseIsEqual(neg(*RHSC))` evaluates to `true` before proceeding with │
│ the transformation. If the check fails, return `nullptr` to avoid applying    │
│ the incorrect transformation.\n\n5. **Conclusion**: The proposed fix ensures  │
│ that the transformation only applies when the negation logic is valid,        │
│ preventing the introduction of poison. This resolves the mismatch observed in │
│ the Alive2 counterexample."})                                                 │
